[[File:Jan v Hocksem, Digitus florum utriusque iuris, 1341 (RHCL Maastricht).jpg|thumb|''Digitus florum utriusque iuris'', 1341]] '''Jean de Hocsem''' or '''Jan van Hocsem''', [[Latinisation of names|Latinized]] ''Johannes Hocsemius'' (1278–1348), was a [[canon (priest)|canon]] and [[scholaster]] of [[Saint Lambert's Cathedral, Liège]].
He was the author of the ''Gesta episcoporum Leodiensium'', a history of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Liège|bishops of Liège]] from 1247 to 1347, the original manuscript of which is now in the [[Royal Library of Belgium]] in [[Brussels]].<ref>''L'Historiographie en Belgique'', exhibition catalogue (Brussels, 1935), p. 22.</ref> It is one of the major sources for the history of the [[War of the Cow]]. A second manuscript survives in the library of [[Averbode Abbey]].<ref>[http://www.narrative-sources.be/naso_link_nl.php?link=866 Jean de Hocsem, Johannes Hocsemius], Narrative Sources in the Low Countries. Accessed 24 June 2017.</ref> A critical edition of the chronicle by [[Godefroid Kurth]] was published in 1927 under the title ''La chronique de Jean de Hocsem''.<ref>Scans available online at http://hdl.handle.net/2268/90817</ref>
In 1341 he wrote a book about [[canon law]], ''Digitus florum utriusque iuris'', one copy of which, in the National Archives (RHCL) in [[Maastricht]], is partly in his own hand.<ref>[http://www.mmdc.nl Maastricht, RA : ms. 215] on website ''mmdc.nl''.</ref>
