'''Jenny Hocking''' FASSA (born 1954) is an Australian academic, author and biographer. She is Research Professor and [[Australian Research Council]] Discovery Outstanding Research Award (DORA) Fellow with the National Centre for Australian Studies at [[Monash University]]. In 2013 she was appointed the inaugural Distinguished Whitlam Fellow at the Whitlam Institute, [[University of Western Sydney]].<ref>http://www.whitlam.org/news_and_events/news/goughs_biographer_appointed_the_whitlam_institutes_inaugural_distinguished_fellow</ref> She was elected a Fellow of the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]] in 2010.<ref>http://www.assa.edu.au/fellowship/fellow/11155</ref> She is currently taking the [[National Archives of Australia]] to court to release the "palace letters" relating to the [[dismissal of the Whitlam government]]. 

== Career ==
Hocking is a biographer, scriptwriter and scholar in [[Australian Studies]], counter-terrorism and [[Australian politics]].<ref>Entry on Jenny Hocking, Who's Who in Australia 2014</ref>  She is the author and co-editor of several books including two books on terrorism, ''[http://filmartmedia.com/?p=1668 Beyond Terrorism: the Development of the Australian Security State]'', first published in 1993,<ref>http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1323077</ref><ref>http://www.ias.uwa.edu.au/masterclass/past/2007/hocking</ref> and [http://filmartmedia.com/?p=200 ''Terror Laws: ASIO, Counter-Terrorism and the Threat to Democracy''] and has presented written and in-person submissions to parliamentary inquiries into Australia's counter-terrorism developments.<ref>Who's Who in Australia 2014</ref> She has written on these and other topics in several press Opinion pieces.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/rn/perspective/stories/2002/733798.htm</ref><ref>‘Story of a High Court judge is a modern tragedy’ ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', Opinion Page, 31 August 2000</ref><ref>'A Cloud Over Journalistic Standards' ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', Opinion Page, 26 January 1999</ref> She is also a scriptwriter and co-scripted [http://filmartmedia.com/?p=401 ''Mr Neal Is Entitled to Be An Agitator''],<ref>http://filmartmedia.com/?p=401</ref> a documentary about former [[Attorney-General of Australia|Attorney-General]] in the [[Whitlam Government]] and High Court judge [[Lionel Murphy]], which won the [[Australian Human Rights Award]] for Best Documentary Film in 1991,<ref>http://www.hreoc.gov.au/about/hr_awards/1991.html</ref> and has been historical consultant on several television documentaries including the 2-part series on [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Gough Whitlam]], ''The Power and the Passion'' (2013), screened on [[ABC Television|ABC-TV]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/documentaries/downloads/whitlam_makingof.pdf | title=Whitlam: The Power and the Passion. The Making of the Documentary | publisher=ABC-TV | accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>

Hocking is the author of three biographies: on Lionel Murphy, [http://filmartmedia.com/?p=204 ''Lionel Murphy: A Political Biography'']; on [[Frank Hardy]], Australian author and communist activist, [http://filmartmedia.com/?p=202 ''Frank Hardy: Politics Literature Life'']; and a two-volume biography of former Labor Prime Minister Gough Whitlam, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120418045550/http://catalogue.mup.com.au/978-0-522-85511-1.html ''Gough Whitlam: A Moment in History'' and ''Gough Whitlam: His Time'']. The first volume was launched by Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] in November 2008. It has been reviewed widely in Australia.<ref>The real Whitlam. It's time we discovered the man behind the political legend, writes Nathan Hollier. ''[[The Age]]'' 10/01/2009</ref><ref>''Sydney Morning Herald'' Ross Fitzgerald ‘The great, great man’ 13 December 2008</ref><ref>''[[Canberra Times]]'', John Warhurst, ‘Canberra and the making of a problematic PM’ 22 November 2008</ref><ref>''[[Illawarra Mercury]]'' 15 November 2008</ref><ref>''[[Adelaide Advertiser]]'', Greg Kelton, ‘This week's selections’ 15 November 2008</ref><ref>Weekend Australian Evan Williams ‘The definitive Gough botherer’ 15 November 2008 and by both Carmen Lawrence and [[Mungo Wentworth MacCallum|Mungo McCallum]] in ''[[Overland (magazine)]]'' 2009</ref> Hocking is a regular guest of Writers Festivals, including the [[Melbourne Writers Festival|Melbourne]] and [[Sydney Writers' Festival|Sydney]] Writers Festivals.

== Awards ==
''[[Lionel Murphy]]: A Political Biography''<ref>{{cite book | title=Lionel Murphy: A Political Biography | publisher=Cambridge University Press | author=Hocking, Jenny | year=1997 | pages=371 | isbn=0-5215-8108-7}}</ref> was short-listed for the 1998 [[South Australian Festival Awards for Literature]] non-fiction award.<ref name=Monash/> ''[[Frank Hardy]]: Politics, Literature, Life''<ref>{{cite book | title=Frank Hardy: Politics, Literature, Life | publisher=[[Lothian Books]] | author=Hocking, Jenny | year=2005 | location=South Melbourne | isbn=0-7344-0836-6}}</ref> was short-listed for the  [[NSW Premier's History Awards]], State Records Prize in 2006;<ref name=Monash>{{cite web | url=http://profiles.arts.monash.edu.au/jenny-hocking/research/ | title=Research: Professor Jenny Hocking | publisher=Monash | accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> ''Gough Whitlam: A Moment in History''<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.mup.com.au/books/9780522857054-gough-whitlam-a-moment-in-history | title=Gough Whitlam: A Moment In History | publisher=Melbourne University Publishing, The Miegunyah Press | author=Hocking, Jenny | year=2009 | pages=496 | isbn=9780522857054}}</ref> was short-listed in 2009 for [[The Age Book of the Year|''The Age'' Book of the Year Award]], the [[Queensland Premier's History Awards]] and the [[Prime Minister's Literary Awards]], and long-listed in the [[Walkley Awards]].<ref name=Monash/> In 2012 ''[[Gough Whitlam]]: His Time''<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.mup.com.au/books/9780522868067-gough-whitlam-his-time | title=Gough Whitlam: His Time| publisher=Melbourne University Publishing, The Miegunyah Press | author=Hocking, Jenny | year=2014 | pages=632 | isbn=9780522868067}}</ref> won the [[FAW Barbara Ramsden Award]] in 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbara Ramsden Award|url=https://www-austlit-edu-au.ezproxy.sl.nsw.gov.au/austlit/page/v151?mainTabTemplate=awardWorksAndAgents&from=20&count=20|website=AustLit|accessdate=14 February 2018}}</ref> and was shortlisted in the [[Prime Minister's Literary Awards]] ([[Prime Minister's Prize for Australian History|Australian History prize]]), the [[Queensland Literary Awards]] (non-fiction award) and the [[National Biography Award]], and long-listed in the Waverley NiB Awards for Literature.<ref name=Monash/>

==Palace letters==
She is currently taking legal action to have the letters between [[John Kerr (governor-general)|Sir John Kerr]] and the Queen during the [[1975 Australian constitutional crisis#Royal involvement|1975 Australian constitutional crisis]] released by the [[National Archives of Australia]].<ref>http://profiles.arts.monash.edu.au/jenny-hocking/</ref>

