{{other people|Manuel Uribe|Manuel Uribe (disambiguation)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} {{Infobox Governor |name = Manuel María Uribe Ángel |image = Manuel Uribe Ángel.gif |caption = Manuel Uribe Ángel, 1889. |office = 12th President of the [[Sovereign State of Antioquia]] |term_start = 10 April 1877 |term_end = 31 October 1877 |predecessor = Silverio Arango Palacio |successor = [[Julián Trujillo Largacha]] |office2 = [[Senator of Colombia]] |term_start2 = 1882 |term_end2 = 1883 |birth_date = {{birth date|1822|09|04|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Envigado]], [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]], [[Colombia]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1904|06|16|1822|09|04|df=yes}} |death_place = [[Medellín]], [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]], [[Gran Colombia|Colombia]] |restingplace = San Pedro Cemetery |restingplacecoordinates ={{coord|6.265619|N|75.561052|W}} |nationality = [[Colombian people|Colombian]] |party = [[Colombian Liberal Party|Liberal]] |spouse = Magdalena Urreta Saldarriaga (1854–1904) |alma_mater = [[Our Lady of the Rosary University]], [[Central University (Colombia)|Central University]], [[University of Paris]] |profession = Physician |religion = Roman Catholic }}
'''Manuel María Uribe Angel''' (4 September 1822 – 16 June 1904) was a Colombian physician, geographer and politician, he has been called the "''father of medicine of Antioquia''" for his contributions to the advances of the practice of [[medicine in Colombia]] and the [[Antioquia Department]]. He was also known outside the realm of medicine for his studies and works on the [[geography of Colombia|geography]] and [[history of Colombia]]. He also served as President of the then [[Sovereign State of Antioquia]] and as [[Senator of Colombia]].
==Life== Manuel María Uribe Angél<ref name="academia">{{cite book |title= Un siglo de gobierno en Antioquia|year=1990 |publisher= Academia Antioqueña de Historia |location= Medellín |oclc= 25004846 |page=345}}</ref><ref name="varones">{{cite book |last1=Mejía Montoya |first1=Alfonso |authorlink1= |last2=Piedrahita Echeverri |first2=Javier |first3=Humberto |last3=Bronx|title=Varones ilustres de Antioquia |year=1979 |publisher=Academia Antioqueña de Historia |location=Medellín |language=Spanish|oclc=6815674 |page=327 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> was born on 4 September 1822 in ''la Magnolia'',<ref name="mua">{{cite web|url=http://www.mua.edu.co/mua/content/view/19/32/ |title=Historia de la Institución |accessdate=29 May 2009 |language=Spanish |publisher=Institución Educativa Manuel Uribe Ángel |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120125850/http://mua.edu.co/mua/content/view/19/32/ |archivedate=20 November 2008 }}</ref> the [[hacienda]] of his parents José María Uribe Arango and María Josefa Ángel Uribe,<ref name="varones"/> both from an educated and well to do family in the town of [[Envigado]], in what was then the Province of Antioquia, now [[Antioquia Department]], during the First Republic or [[Gran Colombia]]. As customary in those times, he was baptized the following day in the [[parish church]] of [[Gertrude the Great|Saint Gertrude]] in Envigado by Felipe de Restrepo.<ref name="academia"/> And years later [[Confirmation (Catholic Church)|confirmed in the Roman Catholic faith]] by the 1st Bishop Antioquia Mariano Garnica y Dorjuela.<ref name="lea"/>
===Education=== His education began in his home town and first taught by Alejo Escobar, and during his youth worked as secretary of the doctor Nicolás de Villa Tirado; the lack of proper education in Antioquia given the fresh independence of the nation, forced Uribe to depart to the capital of the country, [[Bogotá]] where he began his studies on 18 October 1836 at the [[Our Lady of the Rosary University|High College of Our Lady of the Rosary]], where he was a student of both his brother Wenceslao, and his uncle Pedro Uribe Arango who were professors at the institution. After graduating from Our Lady of the Rosary, he moved on to study Medicine at the [[Central University (Colombia)|Central University of the Republic]], from where he graduated in 1844 as [[Doctor of Medicine|Doctor in Medicine]] and [[surgeon|Surgery]].<ref name="boletin">{{cite book |last1=Academia Nacional de Historia|editor1-first=Pedro M.|editor1-last=Ibañez|title=Boletín de historia y antigüedades |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZqzNAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 May 2009 |year=1904|publisher=Imprenta Nacional |location=Bogotá|language=Spanish |issn=0006-6303 |oclc=1606508|pages=271–280 |volume=II}}</ref>
After graduating he moved for a short time back to Antiquia, but soon began a life of travelling, living in [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]] where he received an honorary degree in Medicine from the [[Central University of Ecuador]], from then to [[Peru]], the United States, and finally to Paris, France, where he lived for two years specializing his medical training.<ref name="boletin"/> Upon his return to Antioquia he married Magdalena Urreta Saldarriaga in 1854, and remained in the country for a good time, practicing medicine, now a renowned man in his field.
Manuel Uribe Ángel developed a renowned fame not only as a doctor, but as a versatile and all-around intellectual socialite. In 1871, after the creation of the Department of Medicine of the [[University of Antioquia]], he joined the institution as a faculty professor of medicine, French, [[Gross anatomy|Gross Human Anatomy]], [[Physics]], [[Residency (medicine)|Residency]], among others.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carrasquilla |first1=Tomás |authorlink1=Tomás Carrasquilla |last2=Bernal Villegas |first2=Leticia |editor1-first=Leticia |editor1-last=Bernal Villegas|others=Ministerio de Cultura : Gobernación de Antioquia |title=Obra escogida |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mtKvSVE_pqMC |accessdate=29 May 2009 |edition=1st |series= |year=2008|publisher=Editorial Universidad de Antioquia |location=Medellín |language=Spanish |isbn=978-958-714-124-5 |oclc=248399354|page=297|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> He was a founder member, 1st and 3rd President of the Academy of Medicine of Medellín,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Botero Restrepo |first1=Juan |title=La Academia de Medicina de Medellín, fundadores y presidentes|year=1988 |location=Medellín |language=Spanish|oclc=23770427|page=8}}</ref> and during the first National Congress of Medicine of Colombia was designated honorary president of the congregation. Member of the [[Colombian Academy of Language|Colombian Academy of the (Spanish) Language]], and the Colombian Academy of History,<ref name="udea">{{Cite journal|url=http://bmedica.udea.edu.co/jbmf/pdf/ManuelUribe.pdf|accessdate=29 May 2009|series=Pioneros de la Medicina Antioqueña|date=31 July 2002|publisher=Universidad de Antioquia|language=Spanish|pages=1–2|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707052637/http://bmedica.udea.edu.co/jbmf/pdf/ManuelUribe.pdf|archivedate=7 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and on 2 December 1903 he was named first president of the Academy of History of Antioquia.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Proyecto de Acuerdo 037 De 2004|url=http://www.concejodemedellin.gov.co/webcon/concejo/concejo_gallery/222.doc|format=Doc|accessdate=29 May 2009|year=2004|publisher=Concejo de Medellín|location=Medellín|language=Spanish|page=2}}</ref>
===Politics=== In 1875, he traveled again to the United States, this tine not only as a mere tourist but as representative of his Government to the United States for the occasion of the Centenary of the death of [[Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra]].<ref name="udea"/> On this occasion he also travelled to [[Mexico]], and the [[Antilles]], but on his return to the country due to the events of the [[Colombian Civil War of 1876]], and the similar wars from then on, he began to venture in to the realm of politics as a member of the [[Colombian Liberal Party]].
In 1877, Uribe participated as [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] of Antioquia during the [[constituent assembly]], becoming its President, and on 10 April 1877 Uribe was elected President of the [[Sovereign State of Antioquia]],<ref name="lea">{{cite book |last1=Osorio Lozano |first1=Nelson |last2=Jaramillo Alzate |first2=José |editor1-first=José María |editor1-last=Bravo Betancur |others=Gobernacion de Antioquia, Academia Antioqueña de Historia, Asociación de Exgobernadores y Exdiputados de Antioquia|title=Gobernantes de Antioquia|url=http://www.lea.org.co/Uploads/documentosCompletos/GOBERNANTES%20DE%20ANTIOQUIA.pdf |accessdate=30 May 2009|date=December 2007|publisher=La Enciclopedia de Antioquia |location=Medellín |language=Spanish|pages=389–391}}</ref> a [[State (administrative division)|state]] in the [[United States of Colombia]]. His administration was challenged by the growing tensions between Liberals and [[Colombian Conservative Party|Conservatives]], Antioquia being a Conservative state was under attack by the Liberal Federal government and under the Military lead of [[Julián Trujillo Largacha]], who succeeded Uribe on 31 October 1877<ref name="lea"/> in power after crushing of Conservative forces.
Uribe Ángel was sent to the [[Sovereign State of Panama]] to Represent Antioquia at the [[groundbreaking]] ceremony for the [[Panama Canal]] on 1 January 1880.<ref name="boletin"/>
In 1882, as a member of the Liberal party, Uribe Ángel was elected [[Senator of Colombia]].<ref name="lea"/>
===Death=== [[File:Manuel Uribe Angel-Busto-Medellin(A).JPG|thumb|Bust by Jairo Cano E. of Manuel Uribe Ángel, located along Avenue la Playa, Medellín. Inscription reads: “Eminent Doctor. Governor of Antioquia.”]] Manuel Uribe Ángel died on 16 June 1904 in Medellín at the age of 81. He had been blind his last seven years, and was only survived only by his widow Magdalena, as they never had children. After his death his body was interred in the San Pedro Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cementeriosanpedro.org.co/Animaciones/recorrido2.swf|format=Flash|title=Recorrido Virtual|language=Spanish|accessdate=29 May 2009|date=28 April 2008|publisher=Fundación Cementerio de San Pedro|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707053325/http://www.cementeriosanpedro.org.co/Animaciones/recorrido2.swf|archivedate=7 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His memory was kept alive as a man of wisdom and science, the Congress of Colombia passed a law commemorating his death and allocating a special endowment to have two oil painting made to consecrate his image, one for his widow and the other to be displayed at the Library of Zea.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Congress of Colombia|title=Leyes |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RpEwAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=29 May 2009 |edition=3rd |series=Colombian Laws|year=1917 |publisher=Imprenta Nacional |location=Bogotá |language=Spanish|oclc=18034454 |pages=9–10 |chapter=Leyes Colombianas Expedidas Por El Congreso de Colombia en sus Sesiones de 1904 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=RpEwAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA129,M1#PPA129,M1 |quote=Ley 6ª de 1904|origyear=1904-09-27}}</ref> In his home town of Envigado there is both a [http://www.hospitalmanueluribeangel.com hospital] and a [https://web.archive.org/web/20080907195710/http://www.mua.edu.co/ educational institute] for secondary education that carry his name.
The Academy of History of Antioquia, honored his contribution by creating the medal ''Order of the Centenary of Manuel Uribe Ángel'', that grants those individuals that contribute to the history of Antioquia, its study, or its preservation; President [[Álvaro Uribe Vélez]] received such distinction on 26 March 2008<ref>{{cite speech|title=Palabras del Presidente Álvaro Uribe al recibir la Orden del Centenario 'Manuel Uribe Ángel', de parte de la Academia Antioqueña de Historia |url=http://web.presidencia.gov.co/sp/2008/marzo/26/11262008.html|date=28 March 2008|accessdate=30 May 2009|publisher=Secretaría de Prensa de la Presidencia de la República|author=Álvaro Uribe Vélez|authorlink=Álvaro Uribe Vélez|location=Medellín}}</ref>
==Works== The following is a list of selected works by Manuel Uribe Ángel in Spanish, some of his works were only published after his death. * {{cite book |title=Reflexiones en viaje: la cruz de barbacoa|publisher=Imprenta de Gutierrez Hermanos|year=1875}} * {{cite book|title=Las empresas del señor Cisneros|url=http://biblioteca-virtual-antioquia.udea.edu.co/pdf/11/history-mua-esc.pdf|year=1880}} * {{cite book |title=Un episodio Colombiano|year=1881}} * {{cite book |title= Geografía general y compendio histórico del estado de Antioquia en Colombia |url= https://books.google.com/?id=YywAAAAAQAAJ|year=1885|publisher= Victor Goupy et Jourdan |location=Paris|oclc= 184810}} * {{cite book |title=Biografía del Dr. Alejandro Eduardo Restrepo y Callejas|publisher=Imprenta del Departamento|year=1889|location=Medellín}} * {{cite book|title=Colón&nbsp;– América&nbsp;– Medellín|url=http://biblioteca-virtual-antioquia.udea.edu.co/pdf/11/11_1470948150.pdf|date=12 October 1892|location=Medellín|publisher=Imprenta del Departamento}} * {{cite book|title=Monumento al salvador del mundo|publisher=Imprenta del Departamento|year=1901}} * {{cite book |title= La medecina en Antioquia |series= Biblioteca Aldeana de Colombia|url=http://biblioteca-virtual-antioquia.udea.edu.co/pdf/40/40_406262920.pdf|publisher= Editorial Minerva|year=1932|location= Bogotá|oclc=2377823}} * {{cite book|title=Discursos y páginas históricas|year=1973|oclc=6146158|series=Colección Academia Antioqueña de Historia}} * {{cite book|title=La serrana : leyenda histórica|year=1984|publisher=Fondo Rotario, Ministerio de Justicia|oclc=26129900|origyear=1895}} * {{cite book|title=Antología del temprano relato antioqueño|url=http://biblioteca-virtual-antioquia.udea.edu.co/pdf/12/lit-atra-jan.pdf|year=1995|location=Medellín|publisher=Biblioteca Virtual de Antioquia}} * {{cite book |others=Prologue by Angela Pérez Mejía|title= Recuerdos de un viaje de Medellín a Bogotá |url= https://books.google.com/?id=Rj4pFbeqx6gC|edition=3rd |series= Colección Narrativa / Patrimonio |year=2007|publisher= Editorial Universidad de Antioquia |location=Medellín |isbn= 978-958-714-011-8 |oclc= 184907942}}
