{{Orphan|date=August 2017}}

'''Mary Harlow''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FSA}} (born 20 October 1956) is an English [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] and [[Classics|classical scholar]]. Her research focuses on various aspects of [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[social history]]―such as age, family, dress and textiles―and their impact on the formation of ancient identity. Her approach strongly promotes interdisciplinarity.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Traditional Textile Craft - an Intangible Heritage?|last=Andersson Strand, Ebert, Harlow, Bjerregaard|first=|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=978-87-998798-0-9|location=|pages=144|quote=To understand the past, and its relationship to our varied presents, requires an open approach to interdisciplinarity. It is essential, to work and learn from craftspeople, archaeologists, anthropologists, economists, artists – and endless other ‘–ists’, and it must become central to further research.|via=}}</ref>

== Education and career==
Harlow studied at the [[University of Leicester]] gaining a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Classical Studies and [[PhD]] in Ancient History. After the completion of her PhD she taught briefly at [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews]], before joining the Institute of Archaeology and Antiquity at the [[University of Birmingham]] as Senior Lecturer in Roman History (1995–2012). Between 1995 and 2000 she was also an Associate Lecturer at the [[Open University]]. In 2000–2002 she held a [[Leverhulme Trust|Leverhulme Research Fellowship]] to study Dress and Identity in Late Antiquity. In 2013 Harlow returned to the University of Leicester where she is now Associate Professor in Ancient History in the school of Archeology and Ancient History.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/departments/archaeology/people/academics/harlow|title=Mary Harlow - University of Leicester|publisher=University of Leicester|access-date=2017-02-23}}</ref>

Between 2011 and 2013 Harlow was also Guest Professor at the Danish National Research Foundation's [[Centre for Textile Research]] (CTR) in [[Copenhagen]], where she took part in the TEMA (Textile Economies in the Mediterranean Area) research project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ctr.hum.ku.dk/about/reports/CTR__rsrapport_2011_with_highlights.pdf|title=CTR annual report 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Since 2015, Harlow has been involved in the international research group ATOM (Ancient Textiles from the Orient to the Mediterranean), in collaboration with CTR and the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]], Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ctr.hum.ku.dk/about/reports/CTR_2015_Annual_Report.pdf|title=CTR annual report 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>

On 15 March 2018, Harlow was elected a [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries]] (FSA).<ref name="FSA">{{cite web|title=15 Mar Ballot Results|url=https://www.sal.org.uk/news/2018/03/15-mar-ballot-results/|website=Society of Antiquaries of London|date=15 March 2018}}</ref>

